text:
HERE US HOW WE CAN SAVE EARTH!!! before it‚Äôs too late...

Change a light 
Replacing one regular light bulb with compact fluorescent light bulb will save 150 pounds of carbon dioxide a year.

Drive less 
Walk, bike, carpool or take mass transit more often. You‚Äôll save one pound of carbon dioxide every mile you don‚Äôt drive!

Recycle more 
You can save 2,400 pounds of carbon dioxide per year by recycling just half of your household waste.

Check your tires
Keeping your tires inflated properly can improve your gas mileage by more than 3 percent. Every gallon of gasoline save keeps 20 pounds of carbon dioxide out of the atmosphere.

Use less hot water 
It takes a lot of energy to heat water. Use less hot water by taking shorter and cooler shower and your clothes in cold water instead of hot water (more than 500 pounds of carbon dioxide saves per year)

Avoid products with a lot of packaging 
You can save 1,200 pounds of carbon dioxide if you reduce your garbage by 10 percent

Adjust your thermostat 
Moving your thermostat down just 2 degrees in winter and up 2 degrees in summer could save about 2,000 pounds of carbon dioxide a year.

Plant a tree 
A single tree will absorb one ton  of carbon dioxide over its lifetime 

Turn off electronic devises 
Simply turn off your tv, DVD player, stereo, and computer, when your not using them, will save you a thousands of pounds of carbon dioxide a year

text: The Earth doesn't need us. The universe doesn't need us. We need it. It is simply a vaguely selfish desire for natural beauty that drives this human urge to save the environment. The world will go on forever; in the end, the Universe will not be affected by human presence. The universe has no conscience, so truly, what is it that we damage when we "destroy" the environment? Not the world. We simply damage our own chances of survival as a species. And who cares if we do so? We'll all die one day and instead of trying to hide from that fact, we should embrace the outstanding beauty of life while we have this unique ability to perceive our own existence. Life and death, it is all beautiful, and existence itself will remain unaffected for all time.

author: StampyLemon

text: ¬†@StampyLemon¬†  If you look at natural history then you will notice how periodic and predictable large scale mass extinctions are. We were overdue for a big one before we even started interfering. Now that we are interfering we are in the middle of one that we caused but the evidence shows that one was on it‚Äôs way anyways. We should always strive to not cause change to Earth but that is literally impossible as long as we live on its fricking surface. Besides mass extinctions are a natural and normal occurrence and are necessary for life to keep going. Mass extinctions clear the path so other species can evolve. The only problem is that we as a species are programmed not to just keel over and die. That leaves us with a dilemma. Do we continue doing what we have been doing? (The stupidest of the options) Do we solve human caused climate change only to be killed by natural climate change later? Do we attempt to figure out the nightmare engineering of colonizing another planet and then the logistical nightmare of somehow transporting every human there? Do we try to terraform our own planet to keep it trapped in the same climate that we evolved with? What I‚Äôm saying is that yes climate change is a problem that we need to solve but what then? As long as we live here we will have an impact and we can never change that. Unfortunately most people don‚Äôt realize that Earth has cycles that can be changed by the slightest difference in air temperature or water vapor or amount of forest. We will be changing the Earth whether we like it or not.

text:
A Cancer On The Host

This is a plea for a pan-national effort to stabilize the use of natural resources and to replace previously depleted organic resources such as trees and coral reefs.  This can only be achieved through global monetary policies that offer both penalties and incentives in conjunction with efforts from committed individuals.  But first, an analogy‚Ä¶

Imagine a Petrie dish, a limited environment, with a nutrient rich substance inside.  Now, introduce an organism that thrives on that nutrient and seal the dish.  

At first, the organism, though much smaller in mass than the nutrient, starts to feed (consume) and soon begins replicating at an unsustainable geometric growth rate.  If enough data is available, a point of demise for the organism can be predicted as it will eventually consume all available nutrients.  This is how cancer behaves if the host cannot stop its spread.  

Now picture earth, a planet with finite resources, (a host of nutrients as it were), similar to the sealed Petrie dish in the above example, evolving through millennia into a stasis of sorts.  Then, like the introduced organism in the Petrie dish, along came humans.

100,000 years ago, the number of humans, like the number of organisms in the Petrie dish example above, was a small enough mass that the consumption of irreplaceable resources and the resulting refuse was not noticeable.  But, as the human mass replicated geometrically, the consumption of resources expanded along predictable lines, the same as cancer expands if not detected early.

However, unlike the Petrie dish example, where there was only one nutrient and one organism consuming that nutrient, humans on earth, though similar to a consuming organism in a sealed dish, have the ability to achieve a balance with the host.  The problem is humans lack the will to do so voluntarily.  Consider this.

According to statistics published in Nature (Nature dooi:10.1038/nature14967 Published online 02 September 2015) there were approximately 6 trillion trees on earth 12,000 years ago,  suggesting trees were the dominant life force at that time.  Today, there is half that number of trees surviving.  

During the past 12,000 years the number of humans on earth has grown from less than a half a billion, to 7.5 billion, and with such numbers, have now become the dominant life force extant. 

Current estimates indicate about 15 billion trees are harvested each year or 2 trees for every human on earth.  Trees are killed for fuel, paper, and lumber, as well as being burned alive to make way for croplands.  But fewer than a billion are replanted.  

The way some humans produce and consume food, burning forests and not allowing topsoil to rest, and chasing profits by offering the least nutrition for the highest profit margin, means nothing will change without a dramatic shift in attitude and mass awareness.  

So, ask yourself: Am I that mindless organism consuming everything I can without thought of what will happen when the host can no longer sustain me, or am I an organism the host generated to help eradicate the cancer?  

When you have your answer, act accordingly.

text:
You know, the biggest and EASIEST thing everyone can do TODAY is talk about climate change. Inform the misinformed and educate the uneducated on the importance of movement towards sustainability. I am shocked at the amount of people who don't know anything about climate change (ex: palm oil / destruction of the Indonesian rain forest and the subsequent endangerment of species). 

The top climate change activists (both scientific and civilian) say we need to talk about it, and talk about it more. When you see that person in front of you at the grocery store using 10+ plastic bags for their groceries, let them know how important it is to shift towards re-usable products. There's no excuse for this other than laziness.

People who post about "WE need to change!" but don't do anything, well talk to people in person rather than leaving comments online, as most people reading those comments are already well versed on the subject.

0.1% - 'We rule this planet!  We own it!  We've got the pieces of paper to back it up, and we've got the guns to enforce our laws and our pieces of paper.'
1% - actually (but ineffectually) Trying to save the planet

Is what we do actually going to get rid of our fundamental economic system, the fundamental practice of which is accumulation for accumulation's sake.  That is, 'more for the sake of more'. I watched this footage with tears in my eyes. 
Beautiful nature always comforted me since I was little. Blue sky, clear water river with many little fishes, rice field in June with many fireflies dancing, shooting star view in night sky....
But I realized many beautiful natures don‚Äôt remain the exact same appearances now..
The clear river I used to play is muddy dirty river.. fireflies had gone because they need real clear water river.. Night view with less star views.. beautiful ocean with many plastic garbage.. 

The article I saw today shocked me. Those plastic in ocean came originally from developed counties and Japan is No.2 country which sent those to other countries.. 
Just everything is packaged unnecessarily here in Japan. People here still think recycling is enough dividing garbage into recycle boxes. Almost people here zero waste equals to recycling. 
It is urgent matter we need to face and tackle.

text:
small things we can do to save our planet:
1. use metal straws
2. switch to renewable energy
3. stop buying plastic bottles/bags. buy renewable ones that can be used many times. take  reusable cups to coffee shops
4. go vegan, even if it's just a few specific days in the week, (this might sound weird but it actually does help)
5. save electricity. do not leave your phone charging overnight. remove plugs from sockets that wont be used overnight
6. save water (shorter showers)
7. take public transport/ walk/ go biking/ car shares
8. dont waste food. start a compost bin. (this can help reduce landfill + give u healthy soil!!)
9. try growing your own fruits & veggies or go to the farmer's market !
10. plant a tree
11. switch your google browser to ecosia, which is a type browser that plants trees for every search!
12. USE YOUR VOICE... this was another person's idea and i literally just copy pasted most of these. it doesn't really matter at this point who started this comment when our planet is dYiNg. if you can, please use your voice to influence others.

text:
I posted this on the creators original but ill repost it here too. 2 years later from this post still landing true, I long to see a day where I watch this a go few got pretty close to the tipping point didn't we, However as days turn to years and governments push for slow acting plans. This message it turns from a message of hope to a video of what could have been, 12 years left to make any meaning full change and governments are talking about change by 2050? Like I'm no PHD holder in maths but that strikes me as a few too many years late. I sit here doing my part walk not driving, eating less meat, supporting regrowth projects but compared to the industry we are fighting its an upwards battle that we won't win until the oil-soaked money stops clouding minds. 


Unfortunately, it'll take a few big worlds extream events for most governments to take notice and by then it'll be too late, our civilisation is based on reaction, not prevention and that's where we will fall is the last hurdle. I hope I'm wrong but that's my thoughts so far and in 23, my mind should be filled with hope, not this right? It feels like we are moving at a crawl when we should be sprinting with all our might desperately grasping for more ground when there are only 12 years left. Just 12, not the 41 or 30 or 20 most leaders are saying.

text: You already know the answer (-;  YouTube has only one goal at any cost: make more money!! I don't think they've ever indicated that they are in the business of humanitarianism and are operating on a purely altruistic basis. It's the manufacturers of all of those glossy documentaries and movies that claim to be attempting to enlighten us and help us save the planet (whilst making heaps of money for themselves in the process) ~ those are the ones you should criticize. YT is actually giving people exactly what they are asking for. What is recommended is only highlighted because feedback from users indicates that's what they're looking for. So blame the millions of idiots who love the junk. YouTube are simply dishing it out as requested ~  free, with some ads thrown in (things they know that most of us are wanting anyway). You might ask National Geographic exactly how sincere they are about saving the planet while you're at it. After all, this video may well be for entertainment purposes only. " Back in September 2015, 21st Century Fox inked a deal with the National Geographic Society that gave Fox a 73% controlling interest in the magazine in exchange for $725 million, an agreement that turned National Geographic into a for-profit company."

text:
¬†@James Rival¬† ¬†King _ G4merr3¬† I respect your opinion.

But earth has always had higher and lower temperatures. When I think of it, does it actually seem possible that we have, people, have increased temperature in 100 years? (Around the time it started with all the co2 stuff and pollution) In 5.000.000.000 years there have been millions and millions major temperature differences, ice ages, and way warmer ages and I don't see why it would be any difference now that we only are such a tiny fragment of Earth's lifespand.

I see it like this: The earth was already warming up when humans even invented cars and things that created pollution. Little did we know that the earth was warming already because of natural reasons. They saw the temperature rising, and we blamed ourself for it, while the pollution's is actually significantly small if you compare. This is just another natural temperature change in Earth's huge lifespand.

I'm not trying to convince you or anything, but it's the way I see it. I respect your opinion aswell.

¬†@Rik L¬† I can see your point of view and understand it, but that doesn't mean that what you are saying in correct.

 From what i understand , global warming is caused by a green house gass called carbon dioxide making it so that more heat is being let in to earth then what is being let out. In nature carbon dioxide is normal and is released by things such as volcanoes and animals. But for those 3 second we have been here on earth we have caused the levels in carbon dioxide to increase, the industrial revolution is one reason why this is happening,  along with our modern ways of farming. It is even seen in graphs, that ever since the industrial revolution CO2 levels have increased dramatically, before that is has been somewhat consistent. In conclusion, yes global warming is caused mostly by human, and how we do things. 

If someone in the comments thinks that some of my facts are wrong they can correct me. I am willing to see other points of view but not without evidence. text:
¬†@Ahmed Ashraf¬† Hey mate, do you know demography? And what it's telling us for some years now? If not, I'm glad to explain to you: We have 6 different stages of the populatin growings. The first is in a really poor country. People there don't live long, they die early, so alot of people have to be born. 2. Stage: The country develops and medicine gets better, people are able to live longer, and the number of people increases. 3. Stage: Because people still get alot of children, population still increases. 4. Stage: People notice know that they don't need six kids, only that 2-3 survive. All six children become adults. So people don't get six children anymore, they will get 1-3. Mostly 2 kids. And if you would draw a diagram, with population, x axis = time, and y axis= amount of people, the line would now be parallel to the y-axis. The populatin doesn't increase anymore. Sometimes the population even decreases, because you need more than 2 children per couple to maintain a stable population number. (If I remember it right, in european countries it was 2.16, but I'm really not sure(!)). As an example, germany's fertility rate (average rate of healty children born per women) is 1.57. It's way under the number you would need to have a stable population. 



So. Conclusion. What is the solution to having to much people on the planet? Simple, and yet hard: Every country needs to become devoped like europe. Because every country goes through these five stages. Some faster, some slower, but they do.


(Sixth stage is a bit a special scenario, which is not important in this discussion.


Have a nice day.
author: Constantin

text:
¬†@Constantin¬† 
Thank you for your explanation 
I have read about these stages by the way and I am all aware of them  (I did not though study demography academicly, and as a science student I believe the final say at any given field should be for the academic people of this field) 
What I meant is not exactly what you got, things like good education, health care, etc. are basic human rights that I hope to live to day where they are provided for every human being. 
But my concern is about how some societies consume what they do not practically need. Alot of people now a days consider the act of shopping itself as a hobby enjoying it, buying stuff without any real need. I don't think this mindset is sustainable by any means.
author: Ahmed Ashraf

But maybe my small text is useful for some people that think that overpopulation (in the meaning of just having too much people) is a problem. The problem is just that the amount people we have now, needs to much.

text: I know this video is trying to promote a less environmentally demanding lifestyle for people but saying we should only eat food with ingredients we can pronounce is kinda flawed, if you get all technical about it many foods have long names because of our naming rules, starch is a polymeric carbohydrate. According to this video's logic  the average consumer  shouldn't buy the scary-sounding polymeric carbohydrate which in the end is just a common ingredient of flour.
author: Meerwasser

text: ¬†@Aditya Yadav¬† I fully get you, not trying to nitpick or undermine anything here, just pointing out that some of the things in the vid Could be interpreted wrong and  lead to some totally bad advice.
author: Meerwasser

text:
¬†@Meerwasser¬† 1. The average consumer is not so smart as to know that starch is a polymeric carbohydrate.
2. Again, people buy flour as ingredient, NOT A POLYMERIC CARBOHYDRATE.
3. Foods don't follow naming rules, the compounds found in them do. Butylated hydroxyanisole¬†(BHA) and Butylated hydroxytoluene (BHT) are preservatives in biscuits and they are named by a rule. Britannica biscuit is NOT NAMED BY A RULE.
4. EXCEPTIONS ARE ALWAYS THERE. SO DON'T BE A SHEEP AND FOLLOW EVERYTHING AS IT IS. USE YOUR OWN BRAIN.
5. If someone can't use their brain, they are watching the wrong video.

text:
Daumants Br≈´ni≈Ü≈° Idk if that‚Äôs a joke (please don‚Äôt woooosh me if it is, just tell me and I‚Äôll delete)

While that may be probable it‚Äôs very unlikely, the orbit of the earth is very stable, and if the planet‚Äôs tilt were to change, then what would change is just the position of the ice caps (you can‚Äôt use the magnetic poles to back yourself up, they‚Äôre already shifting but the earth remains unaffected until the switch is complete). The Earth IS warming actually, and there IS climate change. The emissions made by cars, old style box air conditioners, trucks, and other things that run on fossil fuels emit CFC (Chlorofluorocarbons) that split O3 atoms and turn them into simpler gases like CO2 I think. That, in turn, damages the ozone layer because it‚Äôs made of O3. The ozone layer blocks most UV rays from the sun, but when it is gone/weakened, all the UV light emitted by the sun will hit Earth, causing skin cancer and of course, a rise in temperature.

This isn‚Äôt just the damage, there are SO many greenhouse gases out there that, instead of keeping heat out, keeps heat inside the atmosphere. This then causes the Earth to heat up even more (which leads to what we know as Global Warming).

author: Andrew Deng

text:
¬†@Andrew Deng¬† - prior to the industrial era, the population was significantly below one billion and never rose above that. The only way the population increased was by our use of coal (primarily, initially) and then petroleum and natural gas - all fossil fuels that are currently changing the chemistry of the atmosphere to our detriment. It is safe to say that the world population was always as big as it was ever going to get at the time with the given level of knowledge and technology.


My figures are based on the standard-of-living of a poor Italian from the '70s (where I lived for a bit): no electronics, grow most of your own food, make your own wine, own and ride a bicycle. They're also based on the amount of arable land (I did the calculation for each country individually). And there are a number of "ecological footprinting" web sites to help you short-circuit the calculations.


I chose to use the same figure for everyone, instead of giving a higher standard-of-living to a select few and simple agrarian to everyone else. If we drop everyone back to the level of growing all your food, no bicycle, and no wine, no books, the world could probably sustain over one billion - until the climate change (which has a few decades of adjustment yet to be realised - even if all the fossil fuels are now left in sequestration) finishes "adjusting" the growing regions and further reducing the carrying capacity.

text: ModernRicky25 Well actually, animals would still go extinct. Yes, humans have cause probably millions of species to go extinct but throughout the Earth's long life, billions of species have gone extinct. There was 5 mass extinctions where a majority of Earth's species were wiped out before humans even existed. Extinct is a natural process and humans are not 100% to blame, thought they have greatly increased the rate leading to what scientists think is the 6th mass extinction. But it's called natural selection. Almost all species have gone extinct, 99.9% of them, because they were weaker. But most of that 99.9% were before humans were around. Humans are not to blame for all extinctions.
